Notes: Went with Noe, Nury, and Madigan by the Hilton. First survey. Generally seemed like a solid site with decent fishes and coral cover, although there was also a lot of algae. Big bommies
25m x 1m colony count; will need to return to do another transect
Decided coral must be 1/2 in the transect to count it

Used this as a training transect with Madigan, but I think the data are still good--swam out from Gump beach up northwards until hit an area with some corals--laid out the transect parallel to shore because of the drop off and boats
Pretty surgey/windy that day with lots of sedimentation; saw a lot of pink spots and discoloration like EH

Jet Ski site. This was a hectic day--tried doing 2 transects for the first time and the camera ended dying before I could finish the last algal transect--had to take a video. The first transect wound up also being mainly in the sand so is probably an under-representation of the coral cover (and an over representation of disease prevalence), but the first transect did have much less coral cover than the second. I was a bit spacy on the second transect (tired after the first) so should check photos to make sure there are no repeats. There were also a lot of loose Porites rus around (but that seemed fairly stable and alive/well), so started counting detached vs. attached (tally below the dashed line on the colony count datasheet and marked by a hand in a d-shape in the photographs). It is pretty hard to tell where one P. rus colony ends and the other begins so some of these might be not 100%, but tried. Also note that I didn't notice any proper "disease" on the P. rus, but rather TONS of snails living on them and some tissue loss due to predation (no gradient in algal colonization, small area relative to the size/number of snails)--I didn't photograph every predation event, but did get a representative sample. However, there was more predation than what I documented.
Both transects had a TON of damselfishes and all tissue loss diagnoses should be made in the context of whether they could be from damselfish bites
TONS of damselfish territory
Ran out of battery at the end--just took a video of the transect for algae/etc. Also there were 3 medium Porites with tissue loss that I didn't get to photograph because of battery
Set up in a line after the last transect, parallel to the shore/crest

Went to this site with Liv on snorkel because Katie had an ear infection. This was the high coral cover site Noe and Nury used by the Intercontinental. Nice coral cover, including some big thickets of A. pulchra (not on this transect) with little algae. Tons of Pavona cactus on this transect/around, but a lot of it seemed dead in some parts (nothing looked active--didn't document except for a couple representative photos). The Porites, etc. colonies seemed more together (less fragmented into smaller bits) here and, although there were actually a good number of P. varians and Psammocora on the larger lesion transect, I didn't see any EH signs/discoloration (maybe one?)

Went with Liv then to Coco B. For branching (P rus, Poc, Pavona cactus, etc.), count the colony as the whole thing even if there are dead parts if it's obvious and there's not an obvious dead half, etc. then you'd just count the live part. TONS of P. cactus here and I actually think most of them had some form of TL maybe? Might be undercounted. Not sure if that was seen on the first transect or if there wasn't any--there definitely wasn't those big patches of TL so maybe there wasn't any on that transect but that's surprsing. ]

Accidentally wrote this as 186 but Liv says it's 185. Tons of nice big Pocillopora--could it be the coral gardeners? We saw their boat nearby but Liv says this about of Poc is normal. Took FOREVER because so many corals and it was a little deeper. Apparently this is normally a bit eel-y but I didn't see any
Quite a few sandy patches but didn't want to swerve so went through them. Also was a huge Acropora thicket that I counted based on what I thought was individual colonies
IF THESE ARE THICKETS THERE IS ONLY 1!!!!

Easier than the first transect at this site--lots of turb/algae, encrusting corals, and Napopora. This is the first site where I thought "hmmm do some of these Porites have Black Band Disease?". TBD on that
Took some pics of white algae competition band, marked as nope in folder. Saw EH on Porites and took. pics of old predation scars(?)- don't think its disease?
SAD site--almost no coral, tons of algae right past the sail boats on public beach. Went with Liv and Katie and finished early (almost no coral)
Windy, almost no coral again (maybe less than transect 1 even?). First day Madigan and I went out and did independent surveys--I think it went well
First independent survey! Lots >EH than TL- smaller colonies too. Lowkey gross site
Damselocity=mid; SIX HOURS;Diverse grossness

Long swim out with Noam to a crest site. Lots of rubble and patchy bommies, high wave action, TONS of sargassum with big colonies of Pocillopora, most of which seemec to have tissue loss. Not as much Porites TL, which we thougt might be because there were almost no damselfish? Waaay less than 163, etc.

VERY shallow--kept beaching ourselves on some of the taller bommies. Tons of coral and significant disease--took us 6 hours (me & Madigan). Lots of water flow (near the pass/crest) with low-mid damselfish abundance (maybe more on Madigan's transect?). Almost didn't finish in time

Deepest site yet with big bommies--lots of turb and some damsels (not a ton though). I think these transects are closer to the actual GPS point (maybe right on top) whereas transect 1 I think was closer to shore/maybe a bit shallower. Used this as a training transect with Ashlyn--worked on Coral ID. Julianna did the first 1/4 of the transect, then Ashlyn took over with Julianna watching, then Julianna took it back for the last 1/5 to rush to finish (colony counts + lesion photos with Madigan). Will do another training day or two (maybe also with Adam)

Lower damselosity than 152 but still some patches. Tons of coral. Adam and Ashlyn used this as training--Ashlyn did first ~10m then Adam did remining ~40m. TONS of corals to photo--left the dock at 7:45 and didn't get back until like 4:00PM. Sad. Bad day where Julianna hit a coral and Ashlyn had chest pain.

a very continous transect, lots of rubble. A LOT of corals, a lot of bummies were very dense and could not look inside/under. a lot of turbeneria all around, and a lot of halamida under some bummies. Very shallow, wind picked up and transect might have drifted somewhat. Adam did alone, confirmed questinable ones with Julianna or Madigan. Got out late and got back before 3pm !

My transect was the patchiest of this site (least coral, most sand, sparse bommies)--if anything this might be an overcount of the corals based on how the transect ended up? Mid damselosity. Diverse, lots of coral. This was the deepest of the 3 transects

I helped Adam with the end of this one. Transect 1 and Transect 3 I did lesions on--there was lots of structure but not a ton of coral--almost no branching. Lots of Por TL and macroalgae and damselfish and sediment. It was a long swim (200m north)
This was a training transect with Ashlyn and Julianna. It was deeper with bommies--lots of turb and some damsels
Ton of nice Pocillopora--Coral Gardeners? Deeper than 134 (okay actually I think I'd just been at bad sites before so was maybe confused about Poc? Liv thought it was normal)

NOTE: Adam thinks this might be a repeat with the one he and Madigan did the day we went out and JJR's data was lost from the hard drive. Should pick this one or that one probably, although Madigan said she thought it was not the same. Can check for that Acropora that was broken to see if it's the algae photos to be sure. Note that this day we also learned Madigan is not recording GA's on Acrop the way JJR is. Big ass eel on this transect--tons of bommies and branching corals. Many damselfish and Turbinaria. I re-did T1 and Madigan and Adam re-did T2. T2 had like no bommies on it--not sure if need to re-do? Probably okay. Adam and I collaborated on this colony count (1/2 1/2). I think this will probably actually become T2 (already a T1 that we recovered), then use my other transect from the day we all went out for T3

Me, Madigan, and Adam all helped on this colony count. Tons of coral, but not much branching (this was right before going to Coco)--a big floating algal raft came over us a couple times and really changed light/temperature. High damselfish abundance and high Por TL (slow to get through this transect)

I did ~3/4 of these colony counts, Madigan did last ~1/4. On T1 here there was TONS of macroalgae and damsels with lots of tall bommies, but less live coral than yesterday. On T3 there was less algae and less structure/it was more patchy. This was the day me/Adam/Madigan went out and got 3 done in a reasonable timeframe (very exciting). Moved T2 once because of an eel

This transect had like no coral on the whole 6m swath (did have an eel). 1st transect was very damsely, had lots of bommies. 2nd transect missed most bommies. There was horrible vis/rain and a weird freshwater layer
